The files in .manager directory are what is causing the problems.  But I 
cannot explain how these files got into the state they are in.  The files are 
the correct length but the last 4 bytes are incorrect (they are all 0 bytes).

This is quite strange because when writing these files we go to great lengths 
to ensure the complete content of the files are flushed to disk.  Here is the 
code we use too try and ensure all data is sync'ed to disk:

	out.flush();
	try {
		((FileOutputStream) out).getFD().sync();
	} catch (IOException e) {
		// just ignore this Exception
		//Debug
		e.printStackTrace();
	}
	out.close();


We flush the stream then we get the actual file descriptor and call sync on it 
then we finally close the stream.  It seems to indicate that Windows Vista may 
have a file caching problem or maybe the hardware is messed up.

Please attach the log file (if it exists) from the workspace when eclipse 
actually launches successfully from a clean configuration.  I'm interested to 
see if any errors were logged when these files were created, which would have 
been during your first successful launch.

Can you tell us if this happens on other machines?  Also what type of file 
system do you use on Windows Vista (NTFS, FAT32, other)? and what are the 
specs of the machine you have Windows Vista on (laptop, desktop, memory, CPU 
etc.)?

Thanks.
